+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01J5avdzfShETgu8chepQDph","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Two failures. Let me trace through the `countBeamPaths` bug. The issue is the \"enqueued once\" approach — when two parent states both reach the same child state, I add their counts correctly to `pathCounts`, but I only enqueue the child once. The child reads `pathCounts` when dequeued, which should have accumulated both parent counts... but only if both parents were processed first.\n\nThe problem: when parent A feeds child C and enqueues C, then parent B (at the same row as A) also feeds C and adds to C's count — but C is already enqueued. When C is dequeued, it will read the (possibly incomplete) count if not all parents at the same row have been processed yet.\n\nThe fix: don't enqueue states at all — instead, process all states by row, ensuring all parents are done before children. Or: track which states have been processed vs just counted.\n\nActually the fundamental bug is simpler: BFS processes in order, but when a state at row R is being processed, other states at row R that haven't been processed yet might also contribute to the same child at row R+1. Since I enqueue each child only once, the child gets enqueued when the first parent processes it, then when dequeued, it reads the current accumulated count (which may be incomplete because other row-R parents haven't run yet).\n\nFix: Process row by row. Collect all states at the current row, then process them all before moving to the next row.\n\nActually a simpler fix: instead of marking states as \"enqueued\" (which prevents re-enqueuing), I should just process each state exactly once when all its parent counts have been accumulated. Since rows are strict, I can group by row."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1569,"cache_read_input_tokens":34838,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_i